Hey everyone,
We’ve been discussing ways to make our Alpha token more competitive and reward our top miners more fairly.

We’re planning to start by burning Alpha tokens to help strengthen the overall token economy and stay on par with other subnets that are already doing this.

From there, we’re thinking about moving those burned tokens into a community treasury — a pool that could later be used to reward the top miners every quarter based on performance. This would create a healthy feedback loop and motivate everyone to keep improving the subnet’s output.

We’d love to hear your feedback on this suggested reward system and how we can make it as fair and impactful as possible. It would be very helpful for us if we can better understand your costs and sharing your github repository so we can make this as open as possible. 

At the same time, we’re also making subnet improvements around:
    1.    Supporting different types of reference materials
    2.    Enhancing semantic labeling for higher-quality data validation

Let’s make this a community-driven upgrade — share your thoughts and ideas below 💬
please let us know by October 8th, otherwise we will start implementing what we think is best.

@Roger | dFusion | $TAO S70 Burning always is a bad idea, we should improve in marketing to bring back more customers, update more use cases for the service we r providing, many solutions. We don't need to apply the worst idea, which is burning emissions; it's just a negative temporary solution. We should fix the root cause!

I agree to a certain point. The problem is that other miners or other subnets are burning most of their alpha token. On our subnets, we have the lowest miners who are not contributing to the value of the subnet but are still getting the value.

I think it would be better to:
1. Reward the better miners
2. Make them more profitable
3. Help the alpha token grow

As the alpha token grows, we can add more functionality to the subnets to do more things. Once we get to that, we can lower the burn. We've been seeing that most of the other subnets are burning, and we're being punished for being too honest in the game.

Hi!  Thanks for making an announcement and opening this discussion before moving ahead — that’s the right approach for something so important.

That said, I have some concerns:

Burning + Increasing Difficulty = Opposing Forces. While I support gradual improvements and higher standards, pairing them with reward reduction will most likely negatively impact overall output quality. 
A “community treasury” isn’t true burning — it’s redistribution. In practice, it shifts rewards from miners to subnet owners. That doesn’t feel fair - that means miners are being taxed while carrying all the operational costs and doing the work.
In case you are concerned with lower performance miners, you could focus on adjusting scoring. For example, further decreasing the weight of new responses to 0.2 or 0.1 would reward consistently good responses more and make the subnet less “gambly.”
